title Fusing Aurora, Vere, and the Arvo boot for Glow's four variants — and a kelvin strategy that names a real tension instead of hiding it
prompt Keaton asked to continue with whatever is best recommended, and to think about fusing Aurora and Vere and the Arvo boot process, following the galaxy small-PR contributing goal, refined to also optimize lowering Zuse's kelvin version to accommodate Glow. Then asked to confirm findings against the live Urbit blog, then Tlon's and Zorp's own sites, before continuing.
think Checked live rather than trust memory or an earlier search's paraphrase, per Keaton's direct ask: fetched urbit.org/blog.md fresh (most recent post: This Month in Urbit, June 2026; the Ares post correctly files under 2023, confirming it as the real, still-in-progress Foundation/Tlon/Zorp next-gen runtime, not stale information), then tlon.io and zorp.io directly (both live, both current, both consistent with the blog's own June 2026 mentions).
think Went looking in our own tree before proposing anything, and found Aurora already named and already designed -- LEXICON.md seats it as Core stack ("the boot -- dawn on open hardware"), and yonder/20260617-195812_aurora-boot-riscv.md already does almost the entire Vere/Arvo-boot-to-RISC-V fusion this ask wanted, stage for stage (pill -> manifest of values, functional BIOS -> privilege relay, larval phase -> precondition gathering, mature kernel -> Caravan waking). Named plainly: Aurora is not a new name to propose, and it is not the same word as Ares -- no collision, no confusion, just two different real things.
think Found the one real gap between that existing document (written before today's Glow/kernel-variants naming work) and where the project stands now: it has one kernel, Caravan, waking at the end of the relay, where we now have a *choice* of four Glow-written variants. Closed that gap narrowly and additively -- one new manifest value (a signed variant-selector fact), read at the same point Urbit's own boot reads pill kind, with the fallback-pair mechanism Aurora already borrowed from ownerboot reused rather than reinvented for holding more than one variant. Deliberately left the two still-open kernel-variant questions (Trey/Triz pairing, meaning of diverse redundancy) unresolved, since the boot relay does not need either answer to work.
think Broke the fusion into a four-rung small-PR ladder per the galaxy grants-format goal, each rung green and independently mergeable before the next opens: the selector fact alone; the relay reading it without acting; a second real minimal kernel stub, selected by name; the fallback-pair mechanism, only once selection itself is proven.
think Took the kelvin question seriously rather than answering it lightly, and found a real tension worth naming plainly rather than smoothing over: rye-versioning-style.md already made a deliberate, reasoned decision to grow Rye only by accretion on a chronological clock, explicitly rejecting the breaking-major-version instinct -- and kelvin, by Urbit's own Stable Arvo blog post, is exactly that breaking instinct, on purpose, counting down toward a hoped-for day of no more breaking changes. Concluded the two are not reconcilable as one internal law, and proposed the honest synthesis instead: keep Glow's own stdlib growing by pure accretion internally, while treating a declared kelvin as an external interop-compatibility label -- the same way Aurora already treats a verified manifest image as an external fact, not an internal law.
think Checked the actual current kelvin at the source rather than estimate it, since this was the one load-bearing fact the whole recommendation rests on: current landed stable is 409 (409k-2, published 2026-03-02); the next kelvin, 408, is already in pre-release testing (408k-rc2, published 2026-06-12) but not yet landed. Read "lowering" the declared kelvin as targeting the current lowest *landed* number (409) rather than an older, higher, more historical one -- serving the small-PR-legibility goal directly, since a PR declaring compatibility with today's kelvin is trivially easier for the real Urbit community to review than one built against a kelvin they have already moved past.
think Named one more real nuance rather than flatten it: Zuse, Arvo, Lull, and Hoon each carry their own separate kelvin number in real Urbit (confirmed via the dated 411k release: zuse 411, lull 323, arvo 237, hoon 138) -- which layer(s) Glow's own interop declaration should actually name is a real open question, not decided here.
file external-research/20260714-013700_aurora-vere-arvo-boot-fusion-and-kelvin-strategy.md why: the full fusion design (extending Aurora's existing boot relay to a choice of four Glow variants), the small-PR ladder, and the kelvin-as-external-label synthesis with the current live number confirmed
recommend check-in -- this is design and research only; no rename, no code, no kelvin number committed. Ready for Keaton's word on the four open questions named at the document's close, most pressingly whether 409 is the right kelvin to declare now versus waiting on 408's landing.
